Had an issue where we were getting this error:

> The version of Vue you are using does not support <script setup>. Please upgrade to 2.7 or above.

But we were using 2.7. Eventually determined the issue was because in response to a security vulnerability scan, we'd forced a specific package version of nanoid (dep of postcss dep of style loader) that was incompatible and was throwing an error. However the code that checks for vue 2.7 explicitly swallows errors and says it is 2.6 or lower if any exception is thrown:

```js{17}
exports.resolveCompiler = function (ctx, loaderContext) {
  if (cached) {
    return cached
  }

  // check 2.7
  try {
    const pkg = loadFromContext('vue/package.json', ctx)
    const [major, minor] = pkg.version.split('.')
    if (major === '2' && Number(minor) >= 7) {
      return (cached = {
        is27: true,
        compiler: loadFromContext('vue/compiler-sfc', ctx),
        templateCompiler: undefined
      })
    }
  } catch (e) {}
```

Not sure the rationale for that, but perhaps at least errors should be printed? I'll definitely grant that specific resolutions in package.json are buyer-beware, but I do wonder the rationale behind swallowing any errors. Does an error likely mean you are on vue 2.6 or lower? In my case it absolutely did not.

(could not include src link or PR as I cannot find v15.10 due to https://github.com/vuejs/vue-loader/issues/2005)

